This is more of a take out place than dine in. They are best known for Pitzas and pita wraps, and they just give more food for the platters. I will say that theres not a lot of variety, but what they serve, they do well.  It took a while for seating (20 mins) but that was also because the outside wasnt open as yet- they have a backyard garden. Its fun to stand in front and watch the pita being made though. Also, they mostly deal in cash.  I tried the merguez sausage wrap and the fava beans for the side, my friend G got the falafels. If you haven't visited this charming neighborhood institution, you might consider that there's something for everyone (vegans, gluten avoiders, carnivores), and so is great for a bunch of friends or a date. Sure, the falafel and hummus are great, but the spinach pie is the secret star of the menu: it's more like a calzone, but better because it has the perfect spinach to cheese ratio and a generous spread of caramelized onions and distinct but subtle spices. I'd also love to know the dark magic that keeps the chicken pitza so moist and flavorful that it doesn't need cheese. The beautifully printed fabric wall hangings make the ambiance as warm as the spices on the lamb pizza (which is delicious with a dab of labneh).

Oh how did it took so long to write this. This has been one of my two go to spot for Mediterranean food in NYC because if their food, service and price.  Food quality is out fresh and delicious which probably the only things you needed to make it outstanding. We usually order sun-dried tomato pizza, definitely their salad mix and a meat or veggie entree to share. Btw that is for  two people and it is plenty and filling. Mix salad you can pick 5 items and I suggest beet and grapeleaves roll. Hummus usually comes with your entree. Sun dried tomato pizza can be a hit or miss because they over cooked mine once but no big deal as burn cheese is heavenly. You definitely need to try other pizza as well such as lamb. Their cheese and spinach roll is always a thing I love to order but I place it at top 4th. I usually get one if I have friends joining us. Entree I would go for their lamb dish or chichen rice wrap up in a naan (ask them for the name).  Price has went up a bit over the time but usually cheaper than most places in the area except McDonald's. For a table of 2, you can walk away with a full belly and weight $40 less. Usually most dishes go for $10 to $14 thou. Btw they don't serve alcohol and bybo isn't an option anymore. But do call them to confirm.  Service can change if busy or not. Usually takes around 5 minutes to get your orders in and about another 10 for food to be served. You should be voice your need as they can be busy. Seating is limited to around 20 inside and outdoor is summer only. Backyard is lovely but can be some mosquito like everywhere else. I probably get one bite every time I am there in the back yard.  Do give this a try if you are near by. It's a vegetarian heaven btw

I also didn’t realize there is a whole room in the back and a little outdoor space. Anyway, for $9 I had the leg of lamb sandwich. Rolled with tomatoes, salad, herbs and onions in a warm, fresh pita. DELICIOUS!  My partner’s falafel was also excellent. Don’t avoid, this place has great, inexpensive, serious food. #yummyinmytummy
Cash only. Probably one of the best places to get middle eastern cuisine near Downtown Brooklyn. Friendly staff. Ideal for small groups.
Great middle eastern food at Great prices.   Always crowded

I really want to love this spot, unfortunately I cannot. The food looks great, but it does not taste as good as it looks. It's deceiving to say the least. I've been here a couple of times to know that the only worthy dish is the pizza, nothing else.  I have tried the falafel sandwich and it tasted awful. The baklava which I am a huge fan of was horrible, the worst I've ever tasted. The lentil soup is bland. I am not a salt eating monster but with my recent change in diet I can easily taste off the bat if something is under seasoned or not.  The cheese pie is the only reliable dish. It is not anything special but it does surpass everything else as far as flavor goes.  The guys here are nice but that cannot and will not compensate for the bad food, sorry guys.

My favorite middle eastern hummus joint outside of Israel. This Jordanian restaurant does it right. They've been here in Brooklyn for decades and bring an authentic flavor and environment to the neighborhood. I would highly recommend the falafel, vegetarian pizza, lentil soup and assorted salads. You will not be disappointed. Will keep coming back for years to come.
Greatfood at a great price
Love the Falafels. Great customer service. Delicious Mediterranean menu.
Fast service, cheap prices, tasty lunch. CASH ONLY.
The food was great
Excellent food but the takeout Lentil Soup and is too pricey for such a small container portion.
Really great food. The bread is simply amazing. Cash only
Great food - love their lentil soup

Excellent, affordable middle eastern restaurant with a wide and varied menu.  I've had most of the dishes on the menu over several years and I've never been disappointed.  Nicely decorated in a comforatble and friendly environment.  Highly recommended.
Good food, service and price. Cash only.

Authentic good and cheap middle eastern food in brooklyn (4) Food (4) Chicken platter: The pita bread is freshly baked hot out of the oven. It comes with every entree but extra pita is only $1. Hummus was silky smooth, perfectly season and very homogeneous. Chicken was a bit dry. Salad was very fresh. Lambjin pitsa was very different. I didn't taste bad but i wasn't crazy about. It was a bit too salty. Service (2 1/2) Service was very average, not good not bad. Decor/ambiance (2 1/2) It seems they used a big carpet was wall paper lol. The bathroom stings. It does seem to have a nice outdoor patio. Very reasonable prices but cash only.
The food was awesome with a family oriented atmosphere.

Spectacular Mediterranean food!  The "plate" meals are super filling and worth it. I ordered the leg of lamb plate and my girlfriend ordered the chicken plate. Both meats were cooked perfectly and coated with herby goodness. Also the house made hummus was super super creamy and delicious. Also the babaganoush was spot on, something I rarely order because it's never done well but they got it right here. My real favorite of the night was pita, fresh crunchy and chewy. Who knew something so simple could taste so good.  Fantastic meal for an affordable price!
While understated from the street, this place is colorfully decorated with some outdoor seating as well. The pitzas are especially good--try the Greens Pitza.
The pita is baked fresh as you order. The zaatar bread is delicious. It's a real gem in Brooklyn with great food. One of my favorite lunch spots.
Good service. Good food

I am amazed at the high ratings this restaurant has gotten.  We had chicken platters with hummus, salad and pita bread.  Nothing on the plate had any flavor.  The hummus was fresh but that is the most I can say;  the chicken was tough and tasteless, the hummus was flavor-wise worse than what you can get in a supermarket and the tomatoes on the salad weren't ripe.  The salad had no dressing.  The tahini sauce was completely bland (which isn't that unusual but it added nothing).  I asked for some lemon and was brought a small cup of bottled lemon juice. We were so angry after this meal that I will never eat here again. Did I mention the servers did not care one bit about how much anyone enjoyed their meal?  All around this place is terrible.
Old skool. Like being in Egypt.

For falafel, pita, hummus, and baba ganoush?  This is my go to place for all four.  They always make their pita fresh (made to order) and their falafel is soft and fluffy instead or weirdly hard like the halal carts.  The hummus is standard, but the baba ganoush is honestly the best I've had.  They have seating in the back that's fairly spacious.  They even has an outdoor patio in the back.
Cool little spot with authentic food at a good price. LOVED their Pitza - yummy with a fresh taste, perfect for sharing with friends or a date.
I had a veggie pizza and soup to go. It was ok
Love it

The place feels a little low rent, but it's not about the atmosphere, it's about the food. This place offers a lot of good to very good food for a very fair price. It's on a easy to access stretch of Atlantic Ave with lots of other food options around there, but I end up here, because it's affordable, the food is interesting, the tables are big enough for larger parties, the servers are super accommodating, and the place is very family friendly.  This is just a solid place to know about and enjoy when you are in the area.
Falafal for  good price, great seating and backyard patio. Can't go wrong at this popular place. Try it!

This casual dining place, also good for takeout, is conveniently located near BAM. We actually discovered this while trying to Google the definition for an actual Bedouin tent, and were delighted not only to find this little gem, but also by the reviews and proximity to our venue. All the five star reviews are true… The food is delicious, and I was adventurous and tried the Loomis drink.

Lentil soup is probably my favorite dish. The only food on planet earth I enjoy that doesn't have meat or dairy in it. The pita bread is out of this world. I can go there and order just puts bread and I will be content. The service is extremely friendly. Definitely my favorite place to eat in the 15 years I've lived in Brooklyn!
Food ok. Service not so good.
this place is LIT !!!! Food is amazing the portions are the best and they are super friendly . i love this place rate it it 100%. this place is way better than king falefel
Fresh and delicious  food.

Not quite as good as it used to be, but still a great value. The pita is delicious, but when we tried to order the feta salad, we were told it was made of all cheese. Nothing else in it. Weird. We got the beet salad, which was a bit bland. Sandwiches are huge.
Neighborhood staple. Budget, no frills, but always delicious.

I've had take out here and also dined in at the restaurant. The ambiance is as close to the culture with the effort put towards it. The quality of the food is amazing. My experience has always been satisfying and in my opinion it seems to improve every time I partake. I appreciate the quality in the food and the customer service matches it. Bedouin is consistent. Thus is an unquestionable 5 stars.
The big portions and tasty food make this place great. Hummus and salad options are really good!

There tebuleh had been prepared without tomato and then had a tomato diced on top just as it was served. I've never seen this done before, and it made for fantastic fresh dish!  The falafel was very fluffy, and quite big.  The hummus was very good, and came with fresh hot pita.  All this, generous portions, and inexpensive!
This is a very good Mediterranean restaurant. The food used to be cheap but they have increased the price now ...
This is my go to place for a great, affordable meal. I especially love the beet salad or the labneh. Everything comes with delicious, freshly made pita.
Very inexpensive, delicious fresh bread and pizza. Get the lambajin. Salad combo is a great deal too. Hummus is incredibly creamy. Some of the best I've ever had.
Food was good (falafel and pita) but the service wasn't great. Indoors was also not an option since it was so warm. Outdoor seating was nice. Prices were fair.

Good food. Inexpensive.
Probably the best pita sandwich I've ever had. Can't wait to try more off the menu.
Fresh made pita. Fresh ingredients. Authentic food. Insane value. Must come often

Everything I have ever eaten at this Mediterranean restaurant is delicious and inexpensive.  Every meal comes with the freshest pita bread you could ever eat.  From the outside, this restaurant looks very small.  Once you enter, you see the dedicated pita-maker and an open kitchen before you enter another room that has the look and feel of a bedouin tent.  The combination of the authentic food and decor transports you to another world.  On a warm day, the restaurant extends further to an intimate outdoor backyard section.
Great value. Vegetables are fresh. Back patio is quiet. Pita is fresh made and undescribably good.

The fresh-baked bread, so chewy and yummy. A hole in the wall with a no-nonsense oven up front makes it really authentic. But the seating in the rear was a delightful surprise. During good weather, the patio seating should be great too.

I've walked past this place so many times and had high hopes for the good smells.  When I finally tried it, I found the food only ok.  Not bad, but not great, and definitely not as good as some other middle eastern restaurants in the area.
Awesome place, love the food, crew and rear garden area. Must try if you are in the area.
